{"timestamp": "2025-11-29 17:17:08.801753", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\nDate: (now)\nScope: host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2, leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1, controller (20.0.0.100)\n\nExecutive summary\n- There is a clear connectivity anomaly: hosts attached to leaf_1 are isolated from the rest of the fabric. Host-to-host traffic within leaf_2 works, but cross-leaf traffic (leaf_1 ↔ leaf_2) fails.\n- Evidence indicates the controller is reachable by the OVS instances (controller shows \"is_connected: true\"), but the forwarding state is inconsistent: leaf_2 has L2 forwarding flows for its local hosts while leaf_1 has a single drop flow and spine_1 has no flow entries. ARP resolution for inter-leaf hosts is failing.\n- Likely localisation of the fault: leaf_1 (primary), spine_1 (secondary) and/or the control application logic that programs those switches. Hosts’ NICs appear up and healthy; the problem appears to be in switch forwarding state or control-plane programming rather than physical host links.\n\nObserved symptoms and tests performed (with key evidence)\n1) High-level reachability scan (get_reachability)\n- Summary: host_2_1 → host_2_2 OK. Several other host-to-host entries were returned as unknown in the initial summary, prompting targeted pings.\n\n2) Targeted pings (parallel runs)\n- host_1_1 → host_1_2, host_1_1 → host_2_1, host_1_1 → host_2_2: all 100% loss, immediate \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- host_1_2 → host_1_1, host_1_2 → host_2_1, host_1_2 → host_2_2: all 100% loss, immediate \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- host_2_1 → host_2_2: earlier overall scan indicated success; during the detailed runs host_2_1 → host_2_2 showed \"Destination Host Unreachable\" in some attempts, but local (self) pings always succeed.\n- Self-pings succeeded (host_1_1→host_1_1 and host_2_1→host_2_1 show sub-ms RTTs).\n\nInterpretation: hosts can use their own stack but cannot reach hosts on other leafs; some intra-leaf connectivity for leaf_2 appears present.\n\n3) Host network config (ip addr / ifconfig)\n- All hosts have correctly configured 10.0.0.x/24 addresses and the local routes point to their eth0. Example: host_1_1 has inet 10.0.0.1/24; host_2_1 has 10.0.0.3/24. No host routing misconfiguration detected.\n\n4) Neighbor (ARP) tables (ip neigh show)\n- Multiple neighbor entries are in state FAILED on hosts:\n  - host_1_1: \"10.0.0.4 dev eth0 FAILED\", \"10.0.0.3 dev eth0 FAILED\", \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\" (i.e. it cannot resolve ARP for other hosts).\n  - host_1_2: similar FAILED entries.\n  - host_2_1: shows 10.0.0.4 lladdr ... STALE (host_2 intra-leaf ARP ok) but other hosts show FAILED.\nInterpretation: ARP resolution fails across leaves; intra-leaf ARP on leaf_2 is OK.\n\n5) Link-level checks (ethtool)\n- Hosts’ eth0 show Link detected: yes and 10Gbps full duplex. Leaf switch physical ports also show link detected: yes. No physical link down reported at NIC level.\n\n6) OVS control-plane state (ovs-vsctl show)\n- Each bridge reports Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" and is_connected: true (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). So the switch-to-controller TCP session exists.\n\n7) OpenFlow features (ovs-ofctl show)\n- leaf_1: ports eth0/eth1/eth2 present; LOCAL (leaf_1) shows PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN. Eth ports show 10GB-FD.\n- leaf_2: ports eth0/eth1/eth2 present; LOCAL shows PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN.\n- spine_1: ports eth0/eth1 present; LOCAL PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN.\n(Note: LOCAL internal interface being LINK_DOWN is observable on all switches here.)\n\n8) Flow tables (ovs-ofctl dump-flows)\n- leaf_1: single flow: \"table=0, priority=100 actions=drop\" — i.e., a drop-all entry (no L2 learn/forward flows present).\n- leaf_2: contains flows that forward between in_port=1↔in_port=2 for MACs of host_2_1 and host_2_2 (shows that leaf_2 has L2 forwarding entries for its local hosts).\n- spine_1: dump returns no flows (empty).\n\nInterpretation: controller has programmed leaf_2 with relevant L2 flows but has not (or cannot) program leaf_1 and spine_1 appropriately; leaf_1 currently drops traffic (drop flow). Because spine_1 has no flows, it will not forward traffic between leaves even if leaf_1 had flows.\n\nLocalization of faulty components\n- leaf_1: Primary suspect.\n  Evidence:\n    - flow table contains only a drop rule (actions=drop).\n    - hosts connected to leaf_1 (host_1_1, host_1_2) cannot ARP or ping other hosts.\n    - leaf_1 OVS shows controller connected, yet necessary forwarding flows are absent.\n- spine_1: Secondary suspect.\n  Evidence:\n    - no flow entries present.\n    - required for forwarding traffic between leaf_1 and leaf_2, but currently empty.\n- Controller / control app: Tertiary suspect.\n  Evidence:\n    - Controller TCP connection is established (is_connected: true) to each switch, but the controller (or its app) is not installing symmetric forwarding state across all switches (it has installed flows on leaf_2, but not on leaf_1 or spine_1). That suggests either a controller application logic issue, a per-switch policy, or a communication problem specific to some switches.\n\nRoot-cause hypotheses (ranked)\n1) Software/control-plane programming inconsistency (most likely)\n   - The controller or its forwarding application is not installing forwarding flows on leaf_1 and spine_1 while installing flows on leaf_2. This explains leaf_2 hosts talking to each other while leaf_1 hosts are isolated. The controller session is present, so failure is likely at the application layer (e.g., topology/DPID mapping, ACLs, or a per-switch decision not to program flows).\n2) Switch identity / topology mismatch or misconfiguration\n   - A mismatch between expected datapath IDs / port names in controller topology mapping could cause the controller to ignore certain switches or ports, leaving them unprogrammed or placing them in a drop/default state.\n   - Evidence in topology listing: the expected ports in the provided topology (e.g., leaf_1:eth3, spine_1:eth2) do not appear in ovs-vsctl outputs — there are fewer ports than the topology description lists. This can cause the controller to have an incomplete view and fail to populate forwarding entries.\n3) Control-plane partition for flow programming (less likely)\n   - Although the controller TCP sessions exist, flow-mod messages could be failing (e.g., application-level errors or OpenFlow version mismatch). The fact leaf_2 is programmed but leaf_1/spine_1 are not suggests selective failure — more consistent with controller logic or per-switch mismatch.\n\nImpact\n- Hosts attached to leaf_1 (host_1_1 and host_1_2) are effectively isolated from hosts on leaf_2 and the rest of the network (cannot resolve ARP for remote hosts or pass traffic).\n- In a larger fabric this would break any multi-leaf east-west traffic and potentially affect services requiring cross-leaf communication.\n\nRelevant raw evidence (selected)\n- Ping failures: \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" (host_1_1 → host_1_2 and others).\n- ip neigh (host_1_1): \"10.0.0.4 dev eth0 FAILED\", \"10.0.0.3 dev eth0 FAILED\", \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\".\n- ovs-ofctl dump-flows leaf_1: \"table=0, priority=100 actions=drop\".\n- ovs-ofctl dump-flows leaf_2: flows present mapping 1↔2 for host MACs (shows local L2 forwarding).\n- ovs-ofctl dump-flows spine_1: no flows returned.\n- ovs-vsctl show (leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1): Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" is_connected: true on all.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic checks (no mitigations applied here; suggestions only for further evidence collection)\n- Check controller logs and the forwarding application log for errors when handling leaf_1 and spine_1 datapaths / ports.\n- Confirm datapath IDs and port names reported to the controller match the expected topology (DPIDs, port names). Look for mismatch or missing ports.\n- Inspect OpenFlow messages (flow-mod/packet-in) on the controller and switch (if logging enabled) to confirm whether flow-mods are attempted and whether switches ack them.\n- On leaf_1 and spine_1, increase OpenFlow debugging/logs to capture any errors when receiving flow-mods.\n- Compare configuration and software versions between leaf_1 (not programmed) and leaf_2 (programmed) to find differences.\n\nFinal assessment\n- Network health: degraded. Local host NICs and physical links appear up, controller connection established, but forwarding state is inconsistent leading to host isolation for leaf_1. The most probable root cause is a control-plane/programming issue (controller application or config) that results in leaf_1 and spine_1 not receiving or not applying necessary flows. Leaf_2 appears correctly programmed and functional for intra-leaf traffic.\n\nIf you want, I can (next) run the suggested diagnostic checks (controller logs, check datapath IDs/port names as seen by controller, collect OpenFlow message logs, or run additional ovs-ofctl / ovs-vsctl queries) to further narrow the root cause.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11172, "output_tokens": 4193, "total_tokens": 15365, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11136}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1920}}}
